      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why L-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>L's strength isn't in its point value — it's in its sheer flexibility. L connects to almost every letter combination, making it one of the best "glue" consonants for building longer words. When you pair L with high-value tiles, the results are dramatic: LOCKJAW (23 points), LUXURY (19 points), and LEXICON (16 points) all demonstrate how L enables access to premium consonants.</p>
      <p>L is also one of the most common letters in 7-letter and 8-letter words, meaning it frequently contributes to bingos (playing all 7 tiles for a 50-point bonus). Words like LUXURIZE and LYRICIZE are potential bingo plays that combine the 50-point bonus with high base values for game-changing turns.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing L-Words</h2>
      <p>L is a workhorse letter that supports multiple strategies. Here's how to get the most from your L tiles:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair L with X for short power plays:</strong> LAX (10 points) and LEX (10 points) are compact 3-letter words that hit hard. On a triple-letter square under the X, LEX scores 26 points.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use L for bingo building:</strong> L appears in many common word endings (-LY, -LE, -AL, -FUL). Keep L on your rack when you have 5-6 good tiles and are one play away from a bingo.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Play -LY suffixes:</strong> Adding -LY to existing adjectives on the board creates adverbs and scores with the word-length bonus. QUICK → QUICKLY adds letters through an existing word.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't hoard multiple L tiles:</strong> With 4 L tiles in the bag, you'll sometimes draw two or three. Having LL on your rack limits options — play one early to keep rack balance healthy.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Remember LYNX:</strong> At 14 points for just 4 letters, LYNX is one of the best short L-words in the game. It's also easy to remember and spot during play.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">L-Word Patterns Worth Knowing</h2>
      <p>Certain L-word patterns appear frequently and are worth committing to memory:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>LU- words:</strong> LUXURY, LUCKY, LUMPY, LUSTY, LURCH — the LU combination leads to many everyday words with decent scores</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>LY- words:</strong> LYNX, LYRIC, LYNCH, LYMPH — short and punchy words that combine L with Y's 4-point value</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>-LE endings:</strong> Hundreds of words end in -LE. When building from existing board letters, look for chances to extend into -CKLE, -NKLE, or -ZLE patterns</span></li>
      </ul>

